WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.040
 So now I want to talk about a concept called virtual hosting.

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:05.640
 Like I said, this doesn't really affect you directly,

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:09.600
 but I want to sort of show you a little bit about how

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:11.560
 an organization like Python Anywhere

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:14.160
 can have a very small amount of resources

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:17.920
 and support a very large number of hosts.

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:20.760
 And this is the idea that they have one piece of hardware

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:23.400
 or a very few pieces of hardware in many different domains

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:25.160
 running on that system.

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:27.280
 And this also kind of helps you understand

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:30.360
 why you have to configure Python Anywhere the way

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:34.720
 you do to help them route the request not just to the server,

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:37.120
 but to your application within the server where

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:38.960
 your application is running.

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:43.800
 So if you recall with the request response cycle, HTTP,

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:45.320
 it makes a connection to a domain,

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:48.640
 and then it sends a GET request with the domain in the GET

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:49.160
 request.

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:51.280
 And so here we have a little sample.

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:54.240
 We say telnet data.pr4e.org.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:57.800
 That's the host and port 80, which is to say,

00:00:57.800 --> 00:00:59.600
 let's talk to the web server.

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:01.960
 And then we connect, and then we send the GET request.

00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:04.400
 And the GET request has a couple of pieces, right?

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:08.000
 The GET request has the name of the document,

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.840
 including the server that it's going to, and then the protocol,

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:12.080
 and then a blank line.

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:15.560
 The key thing is they don't just say, get me any document.

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:18.400
 You actually tell it the host that you're looking for.

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:22.520
 And by looking at this, that's how the virtual hosting works.

00:01:22.520 --> 00:01:25.800
 And so it says, oh, I'm one host really,

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:27.880
 but I can pretend to be many hosts

00:01:27.880 --> 00:01:32.080
 and know which host I'm being asked for with that information.

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:34.080
 And so that's how the virtual hosting works.

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:37.120
 So when a GET request comes into a server,

00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:39.960
 it can say, I have many virtual hosts inside myself,

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:41.520
 and I'll pick the right one.

00:01:41.520 --> 00:01:46.200
 And so if we look at the browser's debugger console,

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:49.160
 we can see that it's asking and doing a GET request

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:54.720
 to a particular Python Anywhere URL with a particular domain

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:55.220
 name.

00:01:55.220 --> 00:01:57.080
 And the domain name is part of the request,

00:01:57.080 --> 00:02:00.760
 which is what makes the virtual hosting happen.

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:03.960
 And so this is where, in the web tab of Python Anywhere,

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:07.680
 you've got to give this thing about where are you at.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:09.680
 And you have to say, within this server,

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:11.280
 I'm running at this home folder.

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:15.120
 And so that's your home directory, dangle projects,

00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:17.040
 local library, your working directory,

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:20.720
 where it's supposed to go when it receives a request for you.

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:24.200
 And then it has this one configuration file.

00:02:24.200 --> 00:02:26.440
 And you'll notice that that file doesn't belong,

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:32.000
 that www.mdntutorial_pythonanywhere.com_wgsi.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.720
 The WGSI configuration file is not in your data space.

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:38.160
 So that's actually in the system.

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:41.360
 And that's the place where the system can look up

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:42.960
 where you're going.

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:45.880
 And then that file, again, if you read that file,

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:48.240
 you'll see it's telling where it's supposed to go

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:50.800
 in the overall system to start in a directory

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:53.680
 and load the configuration for a particular application.

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:55.200
 And up you go.

00:02:55.200 --> 00:02:58.000
 And so this is kind of the picture of how it all works.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:02:59.680
 You've got a browser out here.

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:02.560
 And the browser is making many requests

00:03:02.560 --> 00:03:05.600
 to this server, which is one piece of physical hardware.

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:07.480
 And then there's a little piece of software.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:11.000
 Often it's an open source software called NGINX.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.080
 And it has a whole bunch of configuration files

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:16.600
 that you put in in their user interface.

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:19.320
 And it has little instances of Django,

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:22.280
 one for each of the domains in those systems.

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:24.920
 And so you're isolated from all the other ones,

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:27.040
 whether it's mdntutorial_pythonanywhere.com,

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:30.680
 dj4epythonanywhere.com, or just some other kind of thing.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:31.720
 It doesn't even have to be Django.

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:33.200
 It can be just about anything.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:36.120
 And so there are these configuration files that allow,

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:38.200
 and all this really accomplishes

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:40.720
 is reusing some of the server hardware

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:43.520
 so that you don't have to have a dedicated piece of hardware

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:46.520
 for every single piece of software.

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:49.920
 And then within that is what I showed you before,

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:53.640
 and that is how the request works in your settings file.

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:57.040
 But the goal of NGINX is getting it to your front door

00:03:57.040 --> 00:03:59.320
 so that your application gets the requests

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:01.160
 that are destined for it.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:05.440
 So this is both how these applications are combined

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:07.160
 into one server using virtual hosting,

00:04:07.160 --> 00:04:09.280
 but also how applications work internally.

00:04:09.280 --> 00:04:12.120
 And so I just wanted to give you a really short overview

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:13.400
 of how this all works.

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:17.360
 So that you can build the picture a little bit

00:04:17.360 --> 00:04:19.240
 at a time over the next few weeks

00:04:19.240 --> 00:04:21.440
 as you learn this material.

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:24.480
 [MUSIC PLAYING]

